# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1923-chicago-white-sox-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The **1900 major league baseball season** began on April 19, 1900.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 14, with the Brooklyn Superbas as the regular season champion of the National League.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The Superbas and runner-up Pittsburgh Pirates competed in the *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, a precursor to the current World Series, over four days, with Game 1 on October 15 and ended with Game 4 on October 18.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The Superbas defeated the Pirates in the best-of-five series in four games.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 season saw the return of a postseason championship series (albeit as a one-off), the *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, following the end of the Temple Cup in 1897.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 season saw the aftermath of the National League contracting from 12 to 8 teams, eliminating the Baltimore Orioles, Cleveland Spiders, Louisville Colonels, and Washington Senators.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The elimination of major-league baseball from these cities prompted the minor league American League to declare themselves as a major league the following year.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 schedule consisted of 140 games for the eight teams of the National League.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams in the league.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] This format had previously been used by the National League during their 1888–1891 seasons.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] This format would last until 1904, which saw an increase of games played.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 19 featuring all eight teams.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season on October 14.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, a precursor to the current World Series, took place between October 15 and October 18.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1901 Chicago White Stockings season** was their first season as a major league team, and their second season in Chicago.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] It was also the inaugural season of American League as a major league.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings had a very balanced lineup, which was led by outfielders Dummy Hoy and Fielder Jones, and scored the most runs in the AL.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] They relied primarily on speed, as Frank Isbell, Sam Mertes, and Jones finished 1–2–3 in stolen bases.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The pitching staff was anchored by Clark Griffith, who went 24–7 with a 2.67 ERA.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1902-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1902 Chicago White Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1902-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Sox had a record of 74–60, finishing in fourth place in the American League.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The 1906 season was the seventh season overall for the Chicago White Sox, and their sixth season in the major leagues.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The Sox won their second American League pennant and their first World Series championship.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The Sox won 93 games in the regular season–– a plateau they would not reach again until the 1915 season–– to claim the pennant, propelled by a historic 19-game winning streak in August.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] They won the league pennant largely on the strength of their pitching staff, as their team batting average of .230 was the worst in the AL.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The 1906 White Sox team became known as the *Hitless Wonders*, having won the American League pennant despite posting the lowest team batting average (.230) in the league.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The team had been in fourth place by the end of July, 7½ games behind the defending champion Philadelphia Athletics, when they went on a 19-game winning streak that drove them into first place.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] No American League team would beat the 19-game winning streak for almost 100 years.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The team made up for their lack of hitting prowess by leading the league in walks, hit batsmen and sacrifice hits.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The White Sox pitching staff had a league-leading 32 shutouts and the second lowest earned run average in the league.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The White Sox then defeated their cross-town rivals, the heavily favored Chicago Cubs in the 1906 World Series.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1923-chicago-white-sox-season] The **1923 Chicago White Sox season** was a season in Major League Baseball.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1923-chicago-white-sox-season] The White Sox finished seventh in the American League with a record of 69 wins and 85 losses.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1923-chicago-white-sox-season] It was notably marked by labor controversy in relation to Kenesaw Mountain Landis a judicial federal judge and Commissioner of Baseball, who made a decision which cut building trade wages in Chicago by 12.5%.
[src:1923-chicago-white-sox-season/1923-chicago-white-sox-season] In response unions called for a labor boycott of the White Sox and Chicago Cubs.
